1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O Nxb5 (6... a6 7. Bd3
{is covered in Iuldachev-Ramaswamy and Iuldachev-Al Sayed.}) 7. Nxb5 Nf6 8. Nc3
(8. d3 O-O 9. e5 {is also interesting.}) 8... d6 9. d3 O-O 10. f5 {It is hard
to say whether this is premature. My instictive reaction is that White should
prepare it with a preliminary 10.Qe1 and perhaps 11.Qh4. From a practical
standpoint, the problem is that playing this sacrifice this early gives Black
a great deal of freedom to choose a defensive setup, and it is not possible to
anticipate all of the reasonable defenses ahead of time.} ({A fantasy line runs
} 10. Qe1 e6 (10... a6 11. Qh4 b5 12. f5 b4 13. Ne2 gxf5 14. Bh6 fxe4 15. Ng5
$1 exd3 16. Bxg7 $1 Kxg7 (16... dxe2 17. Rxf6 $3 Kxg7 18. Qh6+ $1 {Pushing the
King away from the Rook.} Kg8 19. Qxh7#) 17. Rxf6 $1 Kxf6 18. Nf4 $1 {This
quiet move defends the key e6 square so that White can play the discovered
check 19.Nge6+.} dxc2 19. Nge6+ Kf5 20. Qg5+ Ke4 21. Re1# {A lovely mating net
with the Knights cooperating in an unusual way to wall the King off from the
d-file.}) 11. e5 dxe5 12. fxe5 Nd5 13. Ne4 b6 14. Bg5 $1 {It is easy to forget,
in the rush to play Bh6, that often Bg5 is even stronger. Here it drives
Black's Queen from the defense of vital dark squares around the King.} Qd7 15.
Qh4 $1 Bb7 {White almost -- almost! -- has enough to crash through here. What
he needs to do is to drive away Black's Knight with c4 without allowing Black
to counterstrike at d3. Two preparatory moves take care of the counterplay.}
16. a3 {Denying Black the use of b4 for his Knight.} Rac8 17. Rad1 {This
defends the d-pawn so that it will not be vulnerable when White pushes c4.} Rc7
18. c4 Ne7 {Now Black's only hope is that White will allow this Knight to
settle in on f5, where it would in fact be an excellent defender.} 19. Bxe7 $1
Qxe7 20. Nf6+ $1 {This forces the darksquare Bishop off.} Bxf6 21. exf6 {Now
the wedge is brutally painful.} Qd8 {Black keeps an eye on the pawn at f6,
momentarily preventing Qh6.} 22. d4 {White threatens to open the d-file,
deflecting Black's Queen from the attack on f6.} Bxf3 23. Rxf3 h5 {Forced --
but now Black's King alone cannot hold all of the dark squares.} 24. Qg5 Kh7
25. Rh3 $1 $18 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Rh3h5] and Black cannot stop mate without
ruinous loss of material.}) 10... Bd7 $2 {This passive move does nothing to
challenge White's plans.} (10... gxf5 {Taking the pawn is a sterner test of
White's sacrificial idea.} 11. Qe1 {This is probably best.} (11. Nh4 fxe4 12.
Nxe4 $17 {It doesn't look like there's enough for the pawn here.}) 11... fxe4
12. dxe4 Qd7 (12... Qb6 13. Qh4 Qb4 14. a3 Qb6 15. Ng5 h6 16. Nf3 Kh7 17. Ng5+
Kh8 18. Nd5 $44) 13. h3 Qe6 14. Qh4 Qc4 15. Bh6 Bxh6 16. Qxh6 Nxe4 17. Rae1 f5
(17... Nxc3 18. Qg5+ $1 (18. Ng5 $2 Qd4+ $19 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Yd4g7]}) 18...
Kh8 19. Qxe7 $1 Kg8 (19... Bf5 20. Qf6+ Kg8 21. Qxf5 Ne2+ 22. Rxe2 Qxe2 23. Re1
Qc4 24. Re4 $18 {[%csl Rc4,Yg4][%cal Re4c4,Ye4g4]}) 20. Qg5+ $1 Kh8 21. Qf6+ $1
Kg8 22. bxc3 $1 Be6 23. Re3 $1 Rfe8 24. Ng5 $1 $18) 18. Nxe4 fxe4 19. Ne5 (19.
Qg5+ Kh8 20. Qxe7 $13) 19... Qd4+ 20. Kh1 Bf5 21. Qg5+ Kh8 22. Rxf5 Rxf5 23.
Qxf5 Qxe5 24. Qxe5+ dxe5 25. Rxe4 Rd8 26. Rxe5 $14) 11. Qe1 a6 $2 {After this
second meaningless move White's attack becomes unstoppable.} (11... gxf5 {
Already this capture is distinctly less appealing than it was a move ago.} 12.
Qh4 fxe4 13. Ng5 {Threatening simple assassination.} h6 14. Ngxe4 {Now the
h-pawn is vulnerable.} Nxe4 15. Nxe4 (15. dxe4) 15... f5 16. Bxh6 Bxh6 {The
only way to survive.} (16... fxe4 17. Qg5 {White mates shortly, e.g.} Rf7 18.
Rxf7 Kxf7 19. Qxg7+ Ke6 20. Qg6+ Ke5 (20... Kd5 21. Qxe4#) 21. Qxe4+ Kf6 22.
Rf1+ Bf5 23. Qxf5#) 17. Qxh6 fxe4 18. Qg6+ Kh8 $11 {and White draws by
perpetual.}) 12. Qh4 b5 {Black seems oblivious to what is happening on the
kingside.} 13. Bh6 Bc6 14. fxg6 (14. Ng5 $1 {is even stronger right away. The
point is that White's Knight hits the e6 square, which could become a forking
point after an exchange of Bishops on g7 and of pawns on g6. Black cannot
afford to recapture on g6 with his h-pawn, for reasons we will see in the game.
He would therefore have to take steps to prevent the fork right away -- but
that doesn't work either, e.g.} Qd7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. fxg6 h6 (16... hxg6 17.
Rxf6 $1 Kxf6 18. Rf1+ $18) (16... fxg6 17. Rxf6 $3 Kxf6 (17... Rxf6 18. Qxh7+
Kf8 19. Qh8#) 18. Rf1+ Ke5 19. Qg3+ Kd4 20. Ne2#) 17. Nxf7 Kxg6 18. Nxh6 Rh8
19. Rxf6+ $3 exf6 20. Rf1 Raf8 21. Qg3+ $1 Kxh6 22. Rf4 $18 {and Black must
give up his Queen to stop mate, after which his d-pawn falls and his whole
position goes to pieces.}) 14... hxg6 {This makes White's task easier.} (14...
fxg6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Ng5 Qd7 17. Rxf6 {as above.}) (14... Bxh6 $1 {This is
the best defensive idea.} 15. Qxh6 fxg6 16. Ng5 Qd7 {White sacrifices on f6 do
not work now because Black's King is not on g7, so the recapture with the pawn
would allow Black to defend h7 laterally with his Queen.} 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5
Qb7 19. Rae1 c4 20. Re6 Kh8 21. Rf3 $18 {The threat of Rh3 is decisive.}) 15.
Ng5 $1 Be8 16. Rxf6 $1 (16. Bxg7 {This move order also works if White follows
up correctly:} Kxg7 17. Rxf6 Rh8 (17... Kxf6 18. Nd5+ Ke5 19. Qg3+ Kd4 20. c3#)
18. Rxg6+ $1 fxg6 19. Ne6+ $1 Kg8 20. Qf4 $1 {[%csl Rd8,Yg7][%cal Yf4f8,Yf8g7,
Re6d8] and Black must lose his Queen or be mated in two.}) 16... Bxf6 {Black
may have thought that he had escaped the worst here, but the fact that the
h-pawn is gone gives White a stunning resource.} 17. Bg7 $3 1-0

