1. e4 c5 2. f4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O Nxb5 7. Nxb5 a6 {
Black reasons that this is not a wasted move because he intends a rapid
queenside expansion.} 8. Nc3 d6 9. d3 b5 {Here come the pawns!} 10. Qe1 Bb7 {
This is the first point at which White has to make a decision. Black hasn't
castled, and until he does, Qh4 doesn't make any sense. So White needs to find
a few quiet moves.} 11. Bd2 (11. Rb1 {also makes sense, freeing the Knight and
Bishop to move later.}) (11. b3 $4 {would be a dreadful blunder here since the
long diagonal is still open. Black wins a full piece with} b4 $19 {[%cal Rg7a1]
}) 11... Qd7 {[%cal Rd7a4] Black is preparing ...b4 by taking control of the
a4 square so that White's Knight will not have that as a place to go.} 12. Rb1
{White, in turn, defends b2 and gets the Rook off of the long diagonal.} b4 13.
Nd1 {Played with a purpose: the Knight is going somewhere.} Nf6 (13... Qa4 14.
Ne3 Qxa2 {would force White to prove that he has compensation for the pawn.}
15. Nc4 Qa4 16. c3 Qc2 17. Qe3 a5 18. e5 d5 19. Rfc1 Qb3 20. Qxc5 dxc4 21. Qb5+
$18) 14. Ne3 {This is a good square for the Knight, particularly since White
has some kingside attacking ideas. One thought is that the Knight on e3 will
support an eventual f5 push. But as we see in this game, that is by no means
the only idea at White's disposal.} O-O 15. Qh4 e6 16. Rbe1 Ne8 17. Ng5 $1 {
This looks like a duffer's move, but it is the prelude to a deep and powerful
sacrifice.} (17. f5 {also gives White a strong attack, e.g.} Bxb2 18. Nc4 $1
Bf6 19. Ng5 Bxg5 20. Bxg5 exf5 21. Be7 Ng7 22. Nxd6 fxe4 23. Bxf8 Rxf8 24. Nxb7
Qxb7 25. Rxe4 $16) 17... h6 18. Ng4 $3 {Simply stunning!} hxg5 19. fxg5 $1 {
[%csl Yf6] This recapture is a vital point. White intends to drop a Knight on
f6, and he needs to be able to recapture with a pawn there.} Qe7 (19... Bxb2
20. Nf6+ $1 Nxf6 21. gxf6 Bxf6 (21... Rfd8 22. Bh6 $1 {and White mates in a
few moves because of the threat of Bg7 and Qh8#}) 22. Rxf6 e5 23. Re3 Kg7 24.
Ref3 $1 Rh8 25. Rxg6+ $1 fxg6 26. Qf6+ Kg8 27. Qxg6+ Qg7 28. Qe6+ Kh7 29. Rh3+
Qh6 30. Qf7#) 20. Nf6+ $1 Nxf6 21. gxf6 Bxf6 22. Rxf6 Rfe8 23. Bg5 $1 1-0

