1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O Nxb5 7. Nxb5 d5 {
Black attempts to get a favorable pawn structure where White's pawn at f4 will
be more awkward than Blacks' pawn at c5.} 8. e5 {Hodgson, a great expert in
this structure, bypasses the d-pawn in order to shut Black's darksquare Bishop
out of the game.} a6 9. Nc3 Bg4 10. d4 {an interesting structural choice.
White wants a favorable sort of Advance French pawn structure. Black is happy
enough with this since it means his lightsquare Bishop isn't locked in. The
resulting positions are interesting and hold chances for both sides.} cxd4 11.
Qxd4 e6 12. Qb4 Bxf3 13. Rxf3 Qe7 14. Qa4+ Qd7 15. Qxd7+ Kxd7 16. Na4 $1 {
[%csl Yb6] This Knight move is critical. White is taking advantage of the
slightly awkward position of Black's King to take over some important squares.}
Rb8 (16... Kc6 $4 17. Rc3+ Kb5 18. Rc5+ $1 Kxa4 19. a3 $3 {Oops.} b5 20. Bd2 $1
{Closing off the retreat at a5.} Ne7 21. b3#) 17. Be3 Ne7 (17... b5 18. Nc5+
$16) 18. Ba7 {Because of Knight forks at b6, Black must move his Rook to an
awkward square.} Rbe8 19. Rb3 b5 {Forced, but now White picks off another pawn.
} 20. Nc5+ Kc8 21. Ra3 g5 22. Rxa6 gxf4 23. a4 $1 {The point is not to create
a passer but to activate the other Rook. Black's King will then find himself
caught in a horrible crossfire.} bxa4 24. Nd3 $1 {Defending e5.} Kb7 25. R1xa4
Ra8 26. Rd6 {Good enough, but White misses a killer tactic here.} (26. Rb4+ $1
Kc8 (26... Kxa6 27. Nc5+ Ka5 (27... Kxa7 28. Rb7#) 28. Rb7 Nc6 (28... Rxa7 29.
b4#) 29. c3 $1 Rxa7 30. b4+) 27. Rxf4 Rf8 28. Rfa4 $18) 26... Nf5 $2 (26...
Rhc8) 27. Nc5+ $1 Kc7 28. Bb6+ Kb8 29. Rxa8+ Kxa8 30. Rd7 {The threat now is
31.Na6 and 32.Ra7# Remember the old saying -- three pieces is a mate!} Kb8 31.
Rc7 $1 {White mates in two.} 1-0

