1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O a6 $6 {By comparison
with the capture on b5, this move looks weak.} 7. Bd3 d6 (7... e6 8. e5 $14 {
If Black moves his d-pawn (either one square or two) White will take it and
play Ne4.}) 8. Nd5 $5 {Iuldachev's trademark.} Bg4 {Black wants to wreck
White's pawn structure -- a sort of mirror image of what White was trying to
do to Black.} (8... e6 {is covered in Iuldachev-Ramaswamy.}) 9. Be2 $1 {Of
course White is not going to allow his pawns to be ruined.} Bxf3 10. Bxf3 e6
11. Ne3 {The best retreat. From here, the Knight lends strength to the f5 push,
nearly forcing Black to prevent it by playing ...f5 himself.} Ne7 12. c3 {The
other point of the Nd5-e3 maneuver: White can play c3, kicking out Black's
strong Knight and blunting the diagonal leading down to b2 so that Black's
Bishop cannot cause mischief.} Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 {The position now is interesting,
unbalanced but not in such a way as to give Black an advantage, which often
happens in some of the more popular lines without 7.Nd5.} d5 14. d3 f5 {Black
plays it before White gets a chance.} (14... d4 15. f5 $1 dxe3 16. f6 Bh6 17.
fxe7 Qxe7 18. Bxe3 Bxe3+ 19. Qxe3 e5 20. Rf3 {~~/+/=}) 15. exf5 exf5 {Now
there is an open file, and this defines the  strategic plans for the next few
moves.} 16. Bd2 O-O 17. Rae1 {White's plan is very simple: he intends to
double up on the open file.} Qd7 18. Re2 Rad8 19. Rfe1 Nc6 20. Nc2 {This move
and White's next make a strong point of d4. There is a subtle positional
reason for this that becomes fully apparent at move 27.} Kf7 21. Be3 b6 $2 {
Black does not understand what is about to happen to the pawn structure.} (
21... d4 22. cxd4 Nxd4 23. Nxd4 Bxd4 24. Kh1 Bxe3 25. Qxe3 Qxd3 26. Qe7+ Kg8
27. Qxc5 Qxe2 28. Rxe2 Rd1+ 29. Qg1 Rxg1+ 30. Kxg1 Kf7 31. Rc2 Re8 32. Kf2 $11)
22. d4 $1 {This paradoxical move locks Black's d-pawn on a light square,
making it vulnerable to attack since Black cannot use his Bishop to defend it.
In fact, from now until the end of the game Black's Bishop is a more or less
useless piece.} c4 23. Bf2 {[%csl Yh4] White's Bishop has h4 as a place to
gain activity.} Rde8 (23... Bf6 {This would be a tougher defense, denying
White easy activity.}) 24. Rxe8 Rxe8 25. Rxe8 Kxe8 26. Ne3 {[%csl Rd5] White's
Bishop is bad, but Black's d-pawn is weak. These two features of the position
are linked, as Iuldachev now proves.} Ne7 27. Bh4 $1 {The point: White will
eliminate the Knight and then win a pawn for free.} b5 28. Kf1 {White realizes
that after the capture on e7, Black's Queen will be looking at the e1 square.
He therefore takes a precaution, bringing his King to the defense of that
square before nipping off the pawn.} b4 {Black desperately tries to drum up
some counterplay by opening the b-file.} 29. Bxe7 bxc3 $5 30. Ba3 $5 {This is
a complicated way to win.} (30. bxc3 $1 {This is simplest. Black's d-pawn
isn't going to run away and he can make no real use of the b-file to get at
White's King.} Kxe7 (30... Qxe7 31. Nxd5 Qd7 32. Qe2+ Kf8 33. Qxc4 $18) 31.
Qxd5 Qxd5 32. Nxd5+ Ke6 33. Ne3 Bf6 34. Ke2 $1 {followed by 25.Nxc4 and 36.Kd3.
}) 30... Bf8 31. bxc3 Bxa3 32. Qxd5 Qb5 33. Qxc4 Qb1+ {These checks run out
pretty quickly.} 34. Kf2 Bf8 (34... Qb2+ 35. Qe2 Kd7 36. Qxb2 Bxb2 37. Nd1 Ba3
38. Ke2 Bd6 39. g3 {and 40.Kd3 and White's pawns start to roll forward with
the assistance of White's King and Knight.}) 35. Nd5 Kd7 36. Qc7+ Ke6 37. Qc6+
1-0

