1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O Nxb5 7. Nxb5 d6 8. d3
Nf6 9. a4 {White discourages later queenside expansion by Black with ...a6 and
...b5, although I don't think this is particularly worrisome.} Bd7 10. Qe1 O-O
$2 {Castling into it.} (10... a6 11. Nc3 e6 12. e5 $1 dxe5 13. fxe5 Nd5 14. Ne4
O-O 15. Nxc5 $16 {and White is close to winning. Black cannot get the pawn
back by} Rc8 16. d4 b6 17. Bg5 Qc7 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19. c3 {and White has a
natural plan of overwhelming the f6 square with Qh4 and perhaps Nd2-e4.}) 11.
Qh4 $1 {[%csl Gd6,Ge7,Yf6,Gf7,Gg6,Gh7][%cal Rf4f5] This is the formation where
White's chances of a kingside attack with f5 are greatest.} Bc6 ({One point
behind leaving the Knight on b5 until it is "invited" to leave is that it
discourages} 11... e6) 12. f5 $1 {I like White's timing here, playing f5 only
after his Queen has reached h4.} a6 {Now the Knight is invited to leave.} (
12... gxf5 13. Bh6 fxe4 14. Ng5 exd3 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Rxf6 $18) 13. Nc3 b5 {
Black is trying to start something on the queenside, but this is much too slow
to give White any problems.} 14. Bh6 b4 15. Ne2 Nh5 (15... a5 16. Ng5 {is
overwhelming.}) 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. fxg6 {Black resigns -- a little surprising,
but his position cannot be held.} (17. fxg6 fxg6 (17... hxg6 18. Ng5 Qe8 (18...
d5 19. Nf4 Rh8 20. Nge6+ fxe6 21. Nxe6+ $18) 19. Ng3 Rh8 {The Rook slips over
to the h-file. Unfortunately, this means the Rook is no longer on the f-file,
so ...} 20. Nxf7 $18) 18. g4 $1 Nf6 19. Ng5 $1 {The chief threat here is Ne6+
with a family fork.} Qd7 20. Rxf6 $1 {The standard tactical shot in such
positions. White gains access to h7.} Kxf6 {This is the only capture that
requires more than a fraction of a second's thought.} (20... Rxf6 21. Qxh7+ Kf8
22. Qh8#) (20... exf6 21. Qxh7#) 21. Rf1+ Ke5 22. Qg3+ Rf4 23. Qxf4#) 1-0

