1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O Nxb5 7. Nxb5 d6 8. d3
Nf6 9. Qe1 O-O 10. a4 Bg4 11. Qh4 Bxf3 12. Rxf3 h6 13. f5 g5 14. Bxg5 $5 {This
is an interesting decision. Whether or not the sacrifice is objectively sound,
Black will be subjected to long-term pressure, and this makes it a good
practical choice for White.} hxg5 15. Qxg5 Nh7 16. Qh5 f6 {This move is a
structural concession by Black. He hopes that White will not find a way to
exploit those light squares -- but this hope proves to be vain.} 17. Rg3 (17.
a5 $5 {This would prevent ...Qb6, which would spare White the need to find
some very exact moves a little later on.}) 17... Rf7 18. Rf1 {Nothing dramatic
is going to happen over the next five moves -- the pawn structure guarantees
that. So White calmly brings another piece up into the attack.} Qb6 19. c4 $5 {
This looks very risky for White.} a6 20. Nc3 Qxb2 21. Nd5 $1 {The main problem
with Black's position is the e6 square, which beckons for a White Knight. If
once a Knight arrives there, White will threaten to put unbearable pressure on
g7 with Qh7.} Qe5 $2 {This turns out not to present much resistance.} (21...
Rb8 22. Nf4 (22. Nc7 $5 Ng5 23. h4 e6 $1) 22... Qd4+ 23. Kh1 Ng5 24. h4 Nxe4
25. dxe4 Qxc4 26. Rd1 Qxe4 27. Ne6 $18 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Yh5h6]}) 22. Nc7 $1 {
Shifting his grip. The Knight will come in at e6 now.} Rc8 23. Ne6 $1 {With
the Knight's arrival on the dream square, White's pressure against g7 becomes
intolerable. The immediate threat is 24.Qg4 with the threat of 25.Nxg7.} Ng5
24. Qg4 $1 {Now White threatens h4 since Black's Knight cannot move.} Kh8 (
24... Nxe6 {fails since after} 25. fxe6 {the Rook cannot move. Note that
White's Queen, from her vantage at g4, defends that pawn on e6 -- otherwise
Black's Queen could simply take it. This is one of the reasons that 24.Qg4 was
far stronger than 24.Qg6.}) 25. h4 Nh7 (25... Nxe6 {still fails to} 26. fxe6
Rcf8 27. Rf5 $1 Qd4+ 28. Kh2 $18 {and there is no good answer to the threat of
29.Rh3+ followed by 30.Qg6 forcing mate.}) 26. Qg6 $2 {This move leaves
White's Queen on babysitting duty for the Rook at g3.} (26. Kh2 $1 {This
accurate move would make 27.Qg6 much stronger.}) 26... Nf8 27. Qh5+ Kg8 $2 ({
Black should have tried giving back the piece with} 27... Bh6 $5 28. Qxh6+ Rh7
{White has no devastating tricks here, so he must give up his h-pawn an enter
the Rook ending with} 29. Qf4 Nxe6 30. Qxe5 dxe5 31. fxe6 Rxh4 32. Rb1 {when
White may not find it easy to win.}) 28. Qg4 Kh7 29. Rf4 Nxe6 30. fxe6 1-0

