1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O a6 {This is a major
decision point for Black.} (6... Nxb5 {is the other major line, and after the
forced recapture} 7. Nxb5 {Black has to decide between 7...d6 and} d5 8. e5 a6
9. Nc3 Bf5 10. d4 {with a basically even position, though White's extra space
gives him a nominal edge.}) 7. Bd3 {It looks very odd to put the Bishop here,
where it blocks the d-pawn. But as the next few moves show, this is just a
temporary state of affairs.} d6 {This is the most common move. Black intends
the ...Bg4 pin.} (7... e6 {invites} 8. e5 $1 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Yc3e4,Re5d6]
when White can take en passant if Black tries to sneak in ...d5. The resulting
positions tend to favor White slightly, especially if his Knight has the use
of e4.}) 8. Nd5 $5 {Iuldachev has made a speciality out of this odd-looking
Knight maneuver. The point is that the Knight is actually more useful at e3
than at c3.} e6 {Black gives up on the idea of ...Bg4 and sets up a "little
center" instead.} (8... Bg4 {is covered in Iuldachev-Al Sayed.}) 9. Ne3 {This
is a remarkably useful square for the Knight. It supports an f5 advance and
also clears the c3 square so that White can, if he likes, boot Black's Knight
out of the center with c3.} Ne7 10. c3 {As advertised.} Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 {White
has a tremendous amount of force behind the f-pawn, and Black must choose now
how to meet the threat of 12.f5.} f5 $1 {This physical block does stop f5, but
it creates some of its own problems in Black's pawn formation.} (11... Nc6 12.
Be2 $14 {White has just a small edge here.}) (11... O-O 12. f5 Nc6 13. Bc2 Ne5
14. Qf2 {already gives White a significant kingside initiative. Notice that
the Knight is very useful on e3, controlling f5 and preparing if necessary to
hop to g4 where it may even help to create mate threats, e.g.} b5 15. f6 Bh8
16. d4 cxd4 17. cxd4 Nc6 18. Ng4 $16 {threatening 19.Nh6#}) 12. exf5 $1 {In
many Grand Prix lines, the proper answer to ...f5 is to bypass the pawn with
e5. Here, however, that simply loses a pawn. Capturing is the right idea.} gxf5
13. g4 $5 {This looks horribly risky. I'm not really sure why White did it
except that Black may otherwise have equality.} (13. Qh5+ Ng6 $13) 13... O-O {
This is safe enough but it is not the sharpest retort.} (13... fxg4 14. Qxg4)
14. gxf5 Nxf5 15. Nxf5 exf5 16. Bc4+ Kh8 17. d3 Qc7 18. Bd5 Rb8 19. Bd2 Bd7 20.
Rae1 Be8 21. Re2 Bc6 22. Rfe1 $14 {Now White has some advantage thanks to his
doubled Rooks.} Qf7 23. Bxc6 bxc6 24. b3 Qd5 25. Qxd5 cxd5 26. Re6 c4 27. Rxd6
$6 (27. d4 cxb3 28. axb3 Rxb3 29. Rxd6 Rb5 30. Rxa6 $16) 27... cxb3 28. Rxa6
bxa2 $2 (28... b2 $1 {minimizes White's advantage, e.g.} 29. Rb1 $14) 29. Rxa2
{Now White has much the same sort of advantage that he could have had in the
note to move 27.} d4 30. c4 Rb3 31. c5 Rc8 (31... Rxd3 32. c6 Rg8 33. Kh1 Rc8
34. Rea1 $18) 32. Rea1 Rxd3 33. c6 Rg8 34. Kf1 Bf6 35. c7 Bg7 36. Ke2 Rh3 37.
Kd1 d3 38. Ra8 1-0

[Event "ADCF Masters"]
[Site "Abu Dhabi"]
