[PlyCount "51"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 e6 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb5 {This pin is what makes the
whole line distinctive. White is, in fact, playing a sort of Nimzoindian
Defense in reverse with a few critical differences: he already has a pawn at
e4, and the pawn at f4 is useful in many lines. The immediate threat is to
double Black's c-pawns with a capture on c6.} Nge7 {Stopping the doubling of
the c-pawns -- for the moment.} 6. exd5 {White opens the e-file because he has
a plan to reinstate the threat of Bxc6+.} exd5 7. Qe2 $1 {With this move,
White pins Black's Knight at e7 and threatens to double Black's pawns by
capturing on c6. It is important to remember this move since it is a key to
gumming up Black's development for the next few moves.} Qd6 {This is
definitely one of the better defensive ideas. Peter Svidler has adopted it.} (
7... Be6 {does not prevent the doubling of the pawns because after} 8. Bxc6+
Nxc6 $4 9. f5 {wins a piece.}) 8. d4 {It is interesting that Iuldachev, who
knows this line extremely well, uses this as his weapon against ...Qd6. White
accepts the odd pawn formation with his pawn on f4 in his own way and hopes to
clamp down on dark squares at d4 and c5. The game illustrates this well.} cxd4
9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. Bxc6 {This capture is the beginning of an interesting
positional plan. One of the benefits of the plan is its simplicity: White is
playing for dark square control.} (10. Be3 $5 {is definitely worth considering.
For example:} a6 11. O-O-O $1 axb5 $2 12. Ndxb5 $1 {Only this Knight: the
other one must stay on target for d5.} Qb8 13. Bb6 Qxf4+ 14. Qd2 $1 Qxd2+ 15.
Rxd2 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Yd6][%cal Rb5c7,Yb5d6,Rc7a8] Because of the mate threat at
d6, Black cannot save his Rook.} Nc8 16. Nc7+ Kd8 {It's perfectly fine to take
the Rook now, but it turns out that there's something even more accurate.} 17.
N7xd5+ {This opens the e-file.} Nxb6 18. Nxb6 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rd7]}) {Now White
has achieved the pawn structure he wants.} 10... bxc6 11. O-O {This defends
the f-pawn and gets the King out of the way.} g6 12. Nb3 {The beginning of a
positional bind strategy. White wants to lock down on the c5 square with his
minor pieces and use that square as a base of operations. The plan is
astonishingly effective.} (12. f5 Bg7 $15) 12... Bg7 (12... c5 13. Rd1 d4 14.
Ne4 $18 {[%csl Rc5] wins some pawns.}) 13. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Yd4] As planned.
Note that White also has enough control over d4 to prevent Black from pushing
through there.} Be6 (13... d4 {fails again, this time to} 14. Rad1 c5 15. Ne4
Qb6 16. Nbxc5 {[%csl Rd7] and the pin is too strong, e.g.} dxe3 17. Nd6+ $1 Kd8
18. Nxf7+ $1 Ke8 19. Nd6+ $1 Kd8 20. Qxe3 $18) 14. Bc5 $1 {Iuldachev wastes no
time gripping the dark squares with his minor pieces. Note the role of White's
Rook at f1 defending the pawn on f4.} Qd7 15. Bd4 $1 {Black's darksquare
Bishop is the lynchpin of his kingside defenses. Once it is traded off,
White's darksquare control will extend across the whole board.} Bg4 16. Qf2
Bxd4 17. Qxd4 {[%csl Yc5] White keeps his grip on c5.} O-O 18. Nc5 Qc7 19. h3
Bf5 20. g4 Bd7 21. Rae1 {The transformation of the position in the past ten
moves is very instructive. White's pieces are all active and his f-pawn will
be on the move as soon as he secures himself against the threat of perpetual
check.} Rae8 22. Nxd7 {This drags Black's queen to an undefended square,
preparing White's next move.} (22. N3e4 {may be an even more accurate way to
achieve the same objective, e.g.} dxe4 23. Nxd7 Rd8 24. Rd1 $18 {and in view
of the threat of 25.Nf6+ Kh8 26.Nd5+! and 27.Nxh7 winning material, Black must
give up the exchange.}) 22... Qxd7 23. Ne4 {Now the family fork threat at f6
is acute.} f6 $2 {This doesn't even slow White down.} (23... f5 $5 {is the
best way for Black to try to confuse the issue. Unfortunately for him, it
isn't quite confusing enough. White keeps a clear advantage in two different
ways:} 24. Nc5 $1 {This is the positional way to keep an edge.} (24. Nf6+ {
This wins material, but White gives Black some piece activity in compensation.}
Rxf6 25. Qxf6 fxg4 26. Qg5 {This pins the f-pawn, preparing f5.} Nf5 (26...
gxh3 27. f5 Nxf5 28. Rxe8+ Qxe8 29. Rxf5 $18) 27. hxg4 Ne3 28. Rf3 d4 29. Rf2
$16) 24... Qd6 25. Re6 Qc7 26. g5 Nc8 27. Rfe1 Nd6 28. R1e5 Qd8 29. b3 $16 {
White now threatens c4. Black is struggling.}) 24. Nxf6+ Rxf6 25. Qxf6 Nc8 26.
f5 1-0

