1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 e6 4. Nf3 Nge7 {This is an anti-Grand Prix setup.
Black makes sure that his Knight is firmly defended before White ever gets in
the Bb5 move.} 5. d4 {White therefore switches plans and plays it like an Open
Sicilian where Black's Knight on e7 may be misplaced.} Nxd4 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7.
Qxd4 Nc6 {Black has found a good square for the remaining Knight, but now he
cannot have a Knight on f6.} 8. Qf2 $1 {An excellent square for the Queen --
safe but active as she can come to g3 or h4 later for a kingside assault. This
is also a theme in the Ciesielski Attack in the Teichmann Defense to the BDG.}
d6 9. Be3 {This stops ...Qb6.} Qa5 10. Bd3 {White intends to castle kingside
-- not queenside, when the open c-file would give Black a very strong attack.}
Be7 (10... Nb4 {allows} 11. Bb5+ {when Black, if he does not want to lose the
castling privilege, must retreat:} Nc6 12. O-O a6 13. Be2 {White now has
Black's Queen nearly trapped, and the encirclement will be complete if Black
greedily targets the c-pawn:} Nb4 $4 14. Bb6 $18) 11. O-O O-O (11... Nb4 12.
Bb5+ {still preserves the Bishop.}) 12. a3 {Sunil knows his opening. Black
should get rid of the lightsquare Bishop at the first opportunity with ...Nb4.
White's thoughtful pawn nudge prevents this.} Bd7 13. Rad1 {[%csl Rd7] The
point of this move is to put the Rook on the same file as Black's undefended
Bishop.} Rac8 14. Qg3 (14. Nb5 $1 {is also very strong because a7 is weak:} a6
$4 15. Bb6 Qa4 16. Nc3 $18) 14... Bf6 15. e5 dxe5 {This sets the stage for a
remarkable kingside assault.} 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Ne4 $1 (17. Rxd7) 17... Nd4
18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Qh4+ Kg7 20. fxe5 Ne2+ 21. Kh1 Qxe5 22. Qg4+ Kh7 {Edge
Trap! What do we need now?} 23. Rf3 $1 1-0

