1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. f4 a6 {Well that's unpleasant! Black prevents White's
favorite Bishop move and prepares fast queenside expansion. Is there any way
to punish such insolence? Not directly: White simply has to know where his
pieces belong.} 4. Nf3 b5 5. d3 Bb7 6. g3 {This is sensible. White puts his
Bishop on the long diagonal.} Nf6 7. Bg2 Qb6 8. Qe2 {White wants to castle,
but he want to be surprised by ...c4+. So he prepares to meet that move with
Be3.} Be7 9. O-O b4 10. Nd1 O-O 11. Kh1 {It's often useful in these Closed
Sicilian positions to take a tempo to move the King off the line of Black's
Queen.} d6 12. Ne3 {A great position for the Knight -- see Iuldachev's pet
line in the Grand Prix (Nc3-d5-e3) for more examples.} Nbd7 13. g4 {One of the
points of having a Knight on e3 is that it supports g4, which in turn supports
f5.} Qb5 14. g5 {Chasing the Knight away from f6 before ramming forward the
other pawn.} Ne8 15. a4 bxa3 16. Rxa3 a5 17. f5 Ne5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Qg4 (19.
fxe6 fxe6 20. Rxf8+ Bxf8 21. Nc4 $18 {[%csl Re5] and Black's e-pawns are
terminally weak.}) 19... f6 20. g6 hxg6 (20... h6 21. Qh5 c4 22. Ng4 {and
there is no stopping a deadly sacrifice on h6.}) 21. fxg6 f5 {Black gives his
Knight the f6 square in order to prevent mate on h7.} 22. Qh3 Nf6 23. Rb3 Qd7
24. Rxb7 $1 {Since a capture on f5 will win back the sacrificed material,
White risks nothing here. And in fact a little calculation shows that with the
elimination of Black's central pawn formation his whole game collapses.} Qxb7
25. exf5 {Ouch!} Qb5 26. Nd5 $5 {A clever finishing shot.} (26. fxe6 $18 {is
also completely adequate.}) (26. Nd5 exd5 (26... Bd8 27. fxe6 $18 {with 28.
Rxf6 and a quick mate coming up.}) 27. Bxd5+ Nxd5 28. Qh7#) 1-0

