1. e4 g6 2. Nc3 Bg7 3. f4 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bb5 d6 6. Bxc6+ $1 {Good timing.
White derives an immediate positional advantage from the doubling of Black's
pawns.} bxc6 7. d3 Rb8 8. O-O Nh6 $6 {Black gets overly fancy with this move.
It isn't dreadful, but it is easy to mishandle the position once you put your
Knights on the rim!} 9. Qe1 {White's flexible multi-purpose move.} O-O 10. f5
$1 {Black's position is already teetering on the brink.} e6 $4 {An
understandable oversight.} (10... gxf5 11. Qh4 Ng4 12. h3 fxe4 (12... Nf6 13.
e5 $1 dxe5 14. Nxe5 Qd4+ 15. Qxd4 cxd4 16. Nxc6 dxc3 17. Nxb8 Bb7 18. bxc3 Rxb8
19. Be3 Nd5 20. Bxa7 Ra8 21. Bd4 Nxc3 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Rxf5 Rxa2 24. Rxa2 Nxa2
25. Ra5 Nc3 26. Ra7 Bd5 27. Rxe7 $16 {and White has searious winning chances.})
13. Ng5 h6 (13... Nf6 14. Rxf6 h6 15. Rxh6 $18 {White can't mate because Black
gets in ...Bf5, but White has collected ample material for the Rook.}) 14.
Ngxe4 f5 15. hxg4 fxe4 16. Bxh6 Bxh6 17. Qxh6 exd3 18. Qg6+ Kh8 19. Kh2 $3 {
and 20.Rh1 will force a quick mate or win gobs of material, e.g.} Qe8 20. Rxf8+
Qxf8 21. Kg3 $1 Qg7 22. Rh1+ Kg8 23. Qe8+ Qf8 24. Rh8+ Kxh8 25. Qxf8+ {etc.})
11. f6 $1 (11. f6 $1 Bxf6 (11... Qxf6 12. Bg5 {traps the Queen.}) 12. Bxh6 $18
{[%csl Yb3][%cal Yb2b3,Rh6f8] Black is a piece down for nothing special.}) 1-0

