1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 d6 5. Bb5 Bg7 6. Bxc6+ $1 {Sunil
understands this opening: given the chance, White should double Black's pawns
at once.} bxc6 7. d3 Nh6 $6 {This isn't a losing move, but this placement of
the Knight has definite disadvantages, as we'll shortly see.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe1
Bg4 10. f5 $1 Bxf3 (10... gxf5 11. Qh4 $1 {[%csl Rh6]} Bxf3 12. gxf3 {[%csl
Rh6] leaves Black's Knight trapped.} fxe4 13. fxe4 e5 14. Bg5 Qb6 15. Bxh6 Bxh6
(15... Qxb2 16. Qg3 Qxc3 17. Qxg7#) 16. Qxh6 Qxb2 17. Qg5+ $1 Kh8 18. Qf6+ Kg8
19. Kh1 Rfe8 20. Qxf7+ $1 Kh8 21. Qf6+ $1 Kg8 22. Rg1#) 11. Rxf3 {Swinging the
Rook up into the attack.} e6 $4 {Many people who play ...Nh6 seem to forget
that it doesn't mix with this nudge of the e-pawn.} 12. f6 $1 {Black's Bishop
on g7 is overworked!} Bxf6 13. Bxh6 {Black is busted.} Bg7 14. Qd2 (14. Bxg7
Kxg7 15. e5 $18 {is simple and strong.}) 14... f5 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. exf5 exf5
17. Re1 Rb8 18. Rfe3 (18. b3 {is simpler and also wins effortlessly.}) 1-0

