1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. f4 Nc6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bb5 Bg7 6. Bxc6+ $1 {Yes! double
those pawns!} bxc6 7. d3 Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe1 {These last three moves are
very nearly automatic against any reasonable Black play. White's Qe1 is a good
double-purpose move: it might mean play on either wing. Now, however, the
thinking starts.} Qb6 10. Kh1 {Common and good. Why leave the King on the hot
diagonal?} c4 11. d4 Bg4 12. Qh4 d5 (12... Bxf3 13. Rxf3 Qxd4 $4 14. Be3 $1 $18
{and Black's Queen is trapped.}) 13. e5 Bxf3 14. Rxf3 Ne4 15. Rh3 $1 {How
about a little threat of mate in one?} h5 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. g4 (17. c3 {is
also possible and looks safer.}) 17... f6 (17... Qxd4 18. Be3 Qxb2 19. Rg1 Qxc2
20. gxh5 Rfb8 21. hxg6 $1 {and White crashes through first, e.g.} Rb1 22. gxf7+
Kxf7 (22... Kf8 23. Rhg3) 23. Qh5+ $1 {No exit!} Ke6 (23... Kg8 24. e6 {and
mate comes on f7 or, if Black prevents that, on h7.}) 24. Qg4+ Kf7 (24... Kd5
25. Qd7#) 25. Qg6+ Kf8 26. Rh8+ $1 Bxh8 27. Qg8#) 18. gxh5 {Open lines!} g5 19.
Qg4 $1 Qxd4 20. Be3 (20. h6) 20... Qd5 (20... Qxb2 21. Rg1 Qxc2 22. h6 Bh8 23.
Qe6+ Rf7 24. fxg5 $18) 21. h6 Bh8 22. Rd1 Qf7 23. h7+ (23. h7+ Kg7 24. e6 (24.
exf6+ {is also effective, e.g.} exf6 25. fxg5 f5 26. Bd4+ $18) 24... Qg6 25. f5
Qe8 26. Bxg5 {and White mates.}) 1-0

