1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. f4 Nc6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bb5 Bd7 {Black breaks the pin, which
reduces the attractiveness of Bxc6. White could (and perhaps should) capture
right away anyway, but in this game he decides to wait until provoked by ...a6
to take the Knight.} 6. d3 Bg7 7. O-O Nf6 8. Bd2 O-O 9. a3 {This move does not
seem to be essential to White's overall plans.} Qb6 10. Qe1 a6 11. Bxc6 Bxc6
12. Rb1 {Defending b2 without creating additional weaknesses.} e6 13. Kh1 {
Once again we see this common preparatory move.} Qc7 14. Qh4 Nd7 15. f5 $1 (15.
e5 {loses a pawn here.}) 15... exf5 16. exf5 Bf6 (16... gxf5 $2 17. Bh6 $1 $16
{gives White a very strong attack. Black's "extra" pawn at f5 is worthless
since it will soon fall.}) 17. Bg5 (17. Ng5 $1 {is even stronger, e.g.} Bxg5 (
17... h5 18. fxg6 fxg6 19. Qc4+ $1 Kh8 20. Ne6 $18) 18. Bxg5 Ne5 19. Rf4 (19.
f6 h5 20. Bf4) 19... h5 20. Bh6 Rfe8 21. Qf6 $1 $18) 17... Bxg5 (17... Bxc3 18.
bxc3 Rfe8 19. f6 {This wedge creates enormous problems for Black.} h5 20. Bh6
$1 {Intending to reposition the Bishop at g7 and then invade with the Queen.}
Re2 21. Bg7 Ne5 (21... Bxf3 22. Rxf3 Re5 {is the toughest defense, though after
} 23. Qf4 g5 24. Qd2 {all that Black has to hold between himself and disaster
is back rank tricks that don't work, e.g.} Rae8 25. Rg3 Re2 26. Rxg5 $1 Rxd2
27. Rxh5 {and White mates quickly.}) 22. Qf4 Ng4 23. h3 Ne5 24. Qh6 Nxf3 25.
Qh8#) 18. Nxg5 h5 19. fxg6 fxg6 20. Ne6 $1 Rxf1+ 21. Rxf1 {[%csl Rc7,Yg7][%cal
Yh4e7,Ye7g7] White's Queen enters at e7 and Black must shed heavy material to
avoid mate.} 1-0

