1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. f4 Nc6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bb5 Bd7 {According to Plaskett's
book on the Grand Prix (2000), p. 23, this setup for Black is perfectly okay
and leads to balanced positions.} 6. O-O Bg7 7. d3 Nf6 {This natural move may
not be best here.} (7... e6 8. f5 $5 exf5 9. exf5 Bxf5 10. Bg5 $44 {
Sutovsky-Kempinski, Polanica Zdroj 1999.}) (7... a6 {Black burns a tempo but
avoids commiting his King to the kingside.} 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Qe1 Qd7 $1 {Again
delaying kingside castling, which could be quite uncomfortable.} 10. Kh1 Nh6
$13 {Rogers-Smyslov, Manila IZT 1990.}) 8. Bxc6 (8. Kh1 O-O 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. f5
Qd7 11. Qe1 gxf5 12. Nh4 $5 $40 {Epishin-A. Petrosian, Groningen 1990.}) 8...
bxc6 {An interesting and questionable choice.} (8... Bxc6 {is obvious and
should yield a roughly equal game with mutual chances.}) 9. Qe1 O-O 10. b3 $1 {
Iuldachev develops flexibly. He has not given up hope of a kingside attack,
but he secures the queenside against ...c4 in order to keep the doubled pawns
in view if he should later want to torment them.} Ne8 11. Bd2 (11. Bb2 {is
also quite reasonable. Often White follows this up with something like Na4,
trying to swap Bishops at a distance.}) 11... Nc7 {The Knight is wandering
away from the kingside.} 12. Qh4 (12. e5 $5 {is Fritz's suggestion.}) 12... f5
{This is the normal prescription against a kingside attack, but in the present
case it is not altogether effective.} 13. Rae1 {This not only centralizes the
Rook but also unpins the Knight.} fxe4 $6 {Black is practically inviting the
Goths into the city with this move, which gives up his blockading pawn at f5
and draws White's other Knight toward g5.} 14. Nxe4 h6 {It is hard even for
grandmasters to resist the temptation to move the pawns in front of their
castled Kings. Let this be a lesson to the rest of us ...!} 15. Ba5 $1 {[%csl
Rc7,Re7] Alert play on both sides of the board! Black's Queen is overworked
now defending c7 and e7.} Rc8 {Black averts immediate tactical disaster, but
the Rook is merely babysitting and the Knight is still pinned.} 16. Re2 {
White's play is very logical: instead of trying anything heroic on the
kingside, he simply doubles Rooks on the half-open e-file.} Be8 17. Rfe1 Qd7 {
Finally unpinning -- but the maneuver has cost a great deal of time.} 18. Bc3
$1 {Black's pieces are clustered clumsily in the center, so this is a good
moment to offer to trade off the one minor piece that is actually defending
something attacked.} e6 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Black's Queen is, of course, busy
defending d6 now.} 20. c4 {Patience. Black's Knight might have come toward the
kingside via d5. With this move, White prevents that.} Qd8 {Trade Queens? Ease
the pressure on my position?} 21. Qg3 {No thank you!} Qe7 $2 {This move is a
very special error, putting the undefended Queen opposite White's massive
battery on the e-file.} 22. f5 $3 {[%csl Rd6] The pawn is undefended, but
Black dare not touch it!} e5 23. Nh4 {[%csl Rg6]} g5 24. f6+ $1 Rxf6 25. Nxf6
Qxf6 26. Rf2 {It doesn't much matter which Rook White moves to this file first;
the other one will join it in a moment.} Qe6 27. Ref1 (27. Nf5+ {is also
strong, perhaps followed by Ref1 and/or h4.}) 27... Rd8 28. Qf3 {That's
TROUBLE on the f-file!} Bd7 (28... gxh4 29. Qf8+ Kh7 30. Rf6 $1 $18 {[%csl Re6,
Yh6][%cal Rf6e6,Yf6h6]}) 29. Qf7+ {The entrance of the Rooks on the seventh
rank and the Knight at g6 seals Black's fate.} Qxf7 30. Rxf7+ Kg8 {Anything
else is even worse.} 31. Ng6 {Now the threat is 32.Ne7+ Kh8 33.R1f6 with a
quick mate.} Ne6 32. Ne7+ {Anyway!} Kh8 33. R1f6 $1 (33. R1f6 Nf8 34. Rxh6+ Nh7
35. Rhxh7#) 1-0

[Event "ISR-chT"]
[Site "Ramat Aviv"]
