[Annotator "McGrew 2006"]
[PlyCount "41"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bb5 Bd7 {Black declines to have his
pawns doubled.} 6. Bxc6 {White takes the Knight anyway. It's better to get rid
of the Knight before it can come to d4, which would be a strong square for
Black because of his strong darksquare Bishop which bears down on that point.}
Bxc6 7. d3 Bg7 8. O-O Nf6 9. Qe1 O-O {Black's structure -- kingside fianchetto,
Knight on f6, pawn still on e7 -- is not designed to withstand a kingside
assault. That is not to say that a White win is automatic, just that Black is
courting danger by setting up like this against the Grand Prix.} (9... e6 {
This waiting move would make a great deal more sense.}) 10. f5 (10. Qh4 {is
also quite strong, preparing f5.}) 10... d5 (10... gxf5 11. exf5 {Recapturing
the pawn is a risk-free way to proceed. White hasn't sacrificed anything, and
Black's castle is greatly weakened because of the missing g-pawn.} (11. Nh4 $5
{This is an interesting idea.} fxe4 12. Nf5 {Now the threat is Qg3 with a
powerful assault on g7.} Kh8 $13 13. dxe4) 11... Qd7 12. Ng5 h6 13. Nge4 $14)
11. Qh4 {A remarkably "human" sort of move from the computer. White sacrifices
the pawn in the name of accelerating the attack.} d4 12. Ne2 gxf5 13. Ng3 $5 {
This is another move that one would have expected more from a human master
than from a computer. White's play is remarkably consistent.} fxe4 14. Ng5 h6
15. Nf5 $1 h5 (15... e3 16. Nxh6+ Bxh6 17. Qxh6 Qd5 $5 18. Rf3 $1 e2 19. Bd2
$18 {[%csl Ge1,Yg3][%cal Yf3g3,Gd2e1]}) (15... hxg5 16. Qxg5 Ne8 17. Nxe7+ $1
Kh8 18. Qh5+ Bh6 19. Qxh6#) 16. Nxe4 {Black's kingside is too weak now, and he
gets slaughtered. The immediate threat is 17.Qg5 Ne8 18.Nxe7+.} Bxe4 17. dxe4
Bh8 18. Bg5 (18. Qg5+ {wins even more quickly:} Kh7 19. Rf3 Rg8 20. Qh6#) 18...
c4 19. Rf3 {Of course. A Rook lift ends matters.} e6 20. Nh6+ Kh7 21. Ng4 $1 {
A lovely double pin.} 1-0

[Event "Ecole d'Echecs U16 op"]
[Site "Bagneux"]
