1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 a6 {This is one of the worst
possible moves.} 6. Bxc6 bxc6 7. d3 d5 {Black clearly doesn't understand these
pawn structures. He makes no effort to keep a pawn at d6 defending c5.} 8. e5 {
White locks out the Black Bishop and prepares to lay siege to the pawn at c5.}
e6 9. O-O h5 {Huh? Whatever.} 10. Na4 Qe7 11. c4 {This prevents Black from
dissolving his positional weakness with ...c4 -- though that is no magic
solution either.} Bb7 12. b3 Nh6 13. Ba3 {There it is!} Nf5 14. Bxc5 {Nice:
White hits the Black Queen and also covers the forking square at e3. When
White has a choice, it is usually best to take this pawn with the Bishop;
taking with the Knight can leave the Knight pinned since the Bishop on a3 is
generally undefended.} Qd8 15. Qe2 {White's Bishop covers the forking square
at e3, but by overprotecting that square White frees his Bishop to do
something else should the need arise. White doesn't have to do anything
spectacular in the next few moves; he's a pawn ahead and can afford to
strengthen his position gradually.} Bh6 16. g3 Ne7 17. Qf2 {White increases
his grip on those dark squares.} a5 18. Rac1 {What!? This looks bizarre, but
it's part of a logical plan. White is going to double Rooks on the c-file and
then open it. There is really not much Black can do to stop it.} O-O 19. Rc3
Re8 20. Rfc1 Nc8 21. a3 Bf8 22. Qd4 Bxc5 23. Nxc5 {Note White's painful grip
on the central dark squares.} Qe7 24. cxd5 cxd5 25. Qa4 {Black's Queen is
overworked here defending b7 and e8.} Rd8 {White now has several ways to win.}
26. Qb5 {An almost effortless positional crush.} (26. Nd4 $1 {is even more
accurate and can lead to a cute tactic based on White's domination of the
c-file and Black's insufficiently defended Bishop at b7, e.g.} h4 27. Ncxe6 $1
fxe6 28. Rc7 {Hey -- how 'bout that open c-file!} Qe8 29. Rxb7 Qxa4 30. bxa4
Re8 31. Rcc7 hxg3 32. hxg3 Ra6 33. Nb5 Rd8 34. Rg7+ Kh8 35. Rh7+ Kg8 36. Rbg7+
Kf8 37. Rxg6 Rc6 38. Nd4 $1 Rb6 39. Rh8+ Kf7 40. Rf6+ Ke7 41. Rh7+ Ke8 42. Nxe6
{etc. with a complete wipeout.}) 1-0

