1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. Bxd7+ Qxd7 7. O-O {White
continues with the Grand Prix pattern.} Nf6 8. d3 O-O 9. Qe1 Nc6 {Time to stop
and think for a moment.} 10. h3 $1 {Because Black's Queen is on d7, White
needs to prevent ...Qg4.} Rab8 11. Qh4 {Now that ...Qg4 has been prevented,
White can play this without fear of a Queen trade.} b5 {Black's standard
queenside counterplay is much too slow here. Aside from the Knight at c3,
which can easily move away, there is really nothing on the queenside for
Black's pawns to bite on.} 12. f5 b4 13. Ne2 a5 {Apparently Black hopes to
play ...a4 and ...a3. But that will be of service to him only if he still has
a darksquare Bishop. So:} 14. Bh6 Ne5 15. Ng5 a4 16. Nf4 Qe8 17. fxg6 hxg6 18.
Nd5 $1 Ned7 (18... Nh5 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. g4 e6 21. Nc7 Qd7 22. gxh5 Qxc7 23.
hxg6 Rh8 24. gxf7 $1 Rxh4 25. Nxe6+ Kg6 26. Nxc7 $18) 19. Nxf6+ {This works,
but White misses a crusher here.} (19. Rxf6 $1 Bxf6 (19... Nxf6 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6
21. Bg7 $3 {forces mate.}) 20. Bg7 $3 {and Black cannot stop mate. This is a
tactical pattern worth remembering!}) 19... Nxf6 (19... exf6 20. Bxg7 fxg5 21.
Qh8#) 20. Rxf6 Bxf6 21. Bg7 $1 1-0

