1. e4 c5 2. f4 Nc6 3. Nf3 g6 4. Bb5 Nd4 5. Nxd4 cxd4 6. O-O Bg7 7. d3 Nf6 8.
Nd2 O-O 9. Nf3 a6 10. Ba4 b5 {This justs chases the Bishop to an active square
where it can assist White in the kingside attack.} 11. Bb3 Qb6 12. h3 d6 13.
Qe1 Bb7 14. Bd2 a5 15. a4 $1 b4 {The pawn structure on the queenside is very
poor for Black. All of the tension on the queenside is gone and White has a
free hand on the kingside.} 16. Qh4 Rac8 {This is a classic case where the f5
break is called for.} 17. f5 $1 gxf5 18. Bh6 fxe4 19. Ng5 {With the Bishop
controling the e6 square, White is set to execute one of the classic
sacrificial patterns.} Rc5 (19... exd3 20. Bxg7 Qc6 $1 21. Rf3 $1 Kxg7 22. Rg3
$1 Kh8 23. cxd3 Qc5 24. Rf1 $18 {and Black has no cost-effective way to stop
Rxf6 and mate on h7.}) 20. Bxg7 $1 Kxg7 21. Rxf6 $1 Rxg5 (21... Kxf6 22. Ne6+ {
The point: this is defended.} Kg6 (22... Ke5 23. Qf4#) 23. Qg4+ Kh6 24. Qg7+
Kh5 25. Qxh7#) 22. Qxg5+ Kh8 23. Rxf7 {Simple and direct. I like it!} 1-0

