1. e4 c5 2. f4 Nc6 3. Nf3 g6 4. Bb5 Bg7 5. Bxc6 bxc6 6. d3 Rb8 7. Nc3 d6 8. O-O
Nh6 $6 9. Qe1 O-O 10. Qh4 (10. f5 gxf5 11. Qh4 Ng4 12. h3 Nf6 13. e5 dxe5 14.
Nxe5 Qd4+ 15. Qxd4 cxd4 16. Nxc6 dxc3 (16... Rb6 17. Nxe7+) 17. Nxb8 Bb7 18.
bxc3 Rxb8 19. Be3 $13) 10... Ng4 (10... f5 11. e5 $1 d5 12. Na4 {[%csl Rc5]} c4
13. dxc4 dxc4 14. Nc3 $14) 11. h3 Nf6 {All that Black has succeeded in doing
with his Knight maneuver is losing time getting the horse to f6. White's moves
have been much more useful, and it's no surprise that White now launches a
devastating attack.} 12. f5 {Black's pawn formation -- the pawn still back on
e7, in particular -- begs for this blow to crack open the kingside.} gxf5 13.
Bh6 Bxh6 14. Qxh6 Rxb2 15. Ng5 Rb7 (15... Rxc2 16. Rf4 $1 {The entry of the
Rook on the h-file settles matters.} Rxc3 (16... e5 17. exf5 $3 {Like I just
said, the entry of the Knight at e4 settles matters!     Seriously, White does
need to conduct the attack with precision and imagination.} (17. Rh4 Re8 18.
Nxh7 Nxh7 19. Qxh7+ Kf8 $19) 17... exf4 (17... Rxc3 18. Rg4 $3 {Uh, make that
the Rook on the g-file!}) 18. Nce4 Bxf5 19. Nxf6+ Kh8 20. Ngxh7 $18) 17. Rh4
Kh8 18. Nxh7 Ng8 19. Qg5 {and White mates.}) 16. Rf4 e5 17. Rh4 {This is the
simplest line, though there is a fantastic sacrificial win that is quicker.} (
17. exf5 exf4 18. Nce4 Bxf5 19. Nxf6+ Kh8 20. Ngxh7 {and White mates with the
discovery.}) 17... Re8 18. Rf1 f4 19. g3 {Black can only sit and suffer while
White opens the f-file and assassinates the guard.} 1-0

