1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O Nxb5 7. Nxb5 d6 8. d3
a6 9. Nc3 Nf6 10. Qe1 O-O 11. f5 gxf5 12. Qh4 d5 13. Bh6 Bxh6 14. Qxh6 d4 15.
Ng5 $3 {This sacrifice turns out to be immaculately timed. It is really quite
extraordinary, because White needs several quiet moves to make the attack work.
The immediate point is that h7 is a focal point, so Black has no time for ...
Ng4 driving White's Queen back. Now White threatens Nd5 bribing the guard, so
Black has no choice.} (15. Nd5 {gives White a good position without any
heartburn:} Ng4 $1 (15... Nxd5 $4 {collapses when White plays} 16. Ng5 $1 Nf6
17. e5 $1 $18) 16. Qh5 e6 17. exf5 exf5 18. Nh4 Qxd5 19. Nxf5 Bxf5 20. Rxf5 Qe6
21. Qxg4+ Kh8 22. Raf1 $16) 15... dxc3 16. bxc3 {[%csl Rd4] This move is
important since it secures the d4 square, preventing Black from using it for a
Queen check.} e5 17. Rf4 $3 Re8 $1 (17... exf4 {is out because after} 18. e5 $1
{the motif of chasing the guard will cost Black his Queen.}) (17... b5 {Doing
nothing doesn't help either, as White invites his other Rook to the f-file as
an assassin.} 18. Raf1 c4 19. Rg4 $3 fxg4 20. Rxf6 $1 {and White mates.}) 18.
Rh4 f4 19. g3 $1 {Prying open the f-file so that the other Rook can join the
attack.} f3 20. Rf1 $1 Re6 21. Rxf3 (21. Rg4 {also wins quickly now that
Black's Bishop doesn't control g4.} Rd6 22. Ne6+ Nxg4 23. Qg7#) 1-0

