1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. d3 Nf6 6. f4 Be7 7. Nf3 O-O 8.
O-O d6 9. Qe1 Re8 10. e5 $1 {Just the right move against this pawn structure.
White will cripple Black's pawns and then play in the center and on the
kingside.} dxe5 11. fxe5 Nd5 12. Ne4 $1 {One of the chief benefits of playing
e5 is that it frees the e4 square so that this Knight can join in the fun.} Qb6
13. c4 Nb4 14. Qg3 f5 (14... Nxd3 15. Bh6 g6 16. Ne1 Nxe1 17. Qf4 f5 18. exf6
$18) 15. exf6 {When you're attacking, it's usually a good idea to open lines.
Here there's the added benefit that Black cannot recapture.} Bf8 16. Ne5 {
Missing a spectacular mate.} (16. f7+ $1 Kxf7 17. Ne5+ $1 Kg8 (17... Ke7 18.
Bg5#) 18. Nf6+ Kh8 19. Nf7#) 16... Kh8 {This allows a spectacular mate anyway!}
17. Ng6+ hxg6 18. Qh4+ Kg8 19. f7# 1-0

