1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 f5 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. e3 d5 $1 {Surprise! White was
probably hoping for 5...Bb4 when 6.Nge2 should give White the edge.} 6. cxd5 {
If White is going to capture the pawn, this is the only way to do it safely.
It won't work to try to capture on d5 with pieces alone and leave the pawn at
c4.} (6. Nxd5 Nxd5 7. Bxd5 (7. cxd5 Nb4 {is about equal, nothing for White to
be proud of in the opening.} 8. d3 Nxd5 {transposes into the game.}) 7... Nb4
$1 {and now White has multiple ways to trip up, e.g.} 8. Qb3 (8. Bg2 $2 Qd3 $1
9. Qe2 Nc2+ 10. Kf1 Qxe2+ 11. Kxe2 Nxa1 $19 {Black will probably get one pawn
for the buried Knight, leaving him the exchange up.}) (8. d4 $2 e4 $1 {and
White is going to get hurt no matter what he does:} 9. f3 (9. Kf1 $1 g6 $1 (
9... c6 10. Bxe4 fxe4 11. Qh5+ $13 {is messier})) 9... c6 10. fxe4 cxd5 11.
exd5 b5 $1 12. a3 bxc4 13. axb4 Qxd5 14. Nf3 Bxb4+ 15. Bd2 Bxd2+ 16. Kxd2 O-O
$15) (8. a3 $2 {Hoping that Black will swap on d5 like a civilized man --
which isn't bad for Black at all. But...} Nd3+ $1 9. Kf1 e4 $1 {and once again
the Bishop finds itself trapped.}) 8... e4 $1 {and Black will play ...c6
picking up the Bishop for a total of three pawns:} 9. f3 Nd3+ 10. Kf1 c6 11.
fxe4 Nc5 $1 {Nice: Black uses the White Queen's exposure to yank the Knight
out of the danger zone without loss of time.} 12. Qc2 cxd5 13. exd5 Bd6 $15) (
6. Bxd5 Nb4 $1 $17) 6... Nb4 $1 {This is Black's clever idea -- he hits the
undefended d3 square at a moment when it is awkward for White to defend it. If
White had already played Nge2, he might castle here and try to evict the Black
Knight later. But if Black settles in on d3 and simultaneously kicks White's
King to the side, the loss of castling will also be painful. All in all, White
almost has to move the d-pawn.} 7. d3 Nfxd5 {Setting one more trap.} 8. Nxd5 (
8. a3 $2 {White cannot brush away the Knight like this because Black has a
Zwischenzug.} Nxc3 $1 {Oops! That hits the Queen, so White has no time to
protect the pawn at d3 after all.} 9. bxc3 Nxd3+ 10. Kf1 e4 $19) 8... Nxd5 {
White has negotiated the rapids and has approximate equality here. One idea
for Black is to play ...Bb4 and swap Bishops on d2. White takes another tempo
to stop that idea.} 9. a3 c6 10. Ne2 Bd6 11. O-O (11. Qb3 {is probably a
little better.}) 11... Qe7 12. Qc2 (12. Qb3 {comes too late now as Black has}
Be6 $15 {The b-pawn is defended laterally and White's Queen needs to move off
of the diagonal before Black starts breaking things with his Knight.}) 12...
O-O 13. e4 Nf6 14. f4 fxe4 15. dxe4 Bg4 16. f5 Bc5+ 17. Kh1 {A little detail:
White's King is now locked in place. Can this be significant? By itself,
probably not. But play on, dear reader, play on ...} Rad8 {Black has only a
modest advantage here, but White has some difficulty organizing meaningful
play.} 18. h3 Bh5 19. g4 $2 {White's sense of danger fails him.} (19. b4 Bb6
20. Bg5 Rd6 21. Rad1 Rfd8 $15) 19... Nxg4 $1 20. Qb3+ {White might have been
counting on this move to save himself, since now the Queen can sweep across
the third rank to block a check at h4. If so, he missed Black's next move.} (
20. hxg4 $4 Qh4+ 21. Bh3 Qxh3#) 20... Bf7 $1 {Black meets the check by hitting
the Queen. This means White has no time to take the Knight.} 21. Qg3 Nf6 {The
upshot is that Black has stolen a pawn in broad daylight. Together with his
positional advantages -- control of the d-file, a weak pawn at e4 to torment,
more active Bishops -- this is enough to win.} 22. Bh6 {A little mate threat ..
. maybe Black will be caught napping?} Bc4 $1 {Guess not.} 23. Rac1 Bxe2 24.
Rxc5 {One more attempt at the mate. Will Black fall into a trance-like state
and recapture on c5?} Nh5 $1 {Guess not. White, with both Rooks and his Queen
en prise, decided to call it a day.} 0-1

