1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 f5 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 {I'm tossing this game in
just because the tactics on the kingside are rather interesting.} 6. e3 d6 7.
Nge2 a6 {Black makes a cubby-hole on a7 for the Bishop.} 8. a3 O-O 9. O-O Ba7
10. b4 Qe8 {Now a kingside attack is in the works. Note that the Bishop on a7
does accomplish one thing that is quite useful: it prevents White from playing
f4. Normally that would be the way for White to nip the attack in the bud. But
here, it would just lose a pawn on e3.} 11. Qc2 (11. f4 exf4 12. Nxf4 Bxe3+ 13.
Bxe3 Qxe3+ 14. Kh1 Ng4 $15) 11... Qh5 12. Nd5 (12. f4 {is still unplayable
because of} Ng4 $1 $19) 12... f4 {So Black has achieved the classic
breakthrough against the g3/f2/e3 pawn structure. This is a genuine pawn
sacrifice; will Black's attack be worth the pawn?} 13. Nxf6+ Rxf6 14. exf4 Bh3
15. Bd5+ Kh8 16. Re1 Raf8 17. Be3 exf4 18. Nxf4 (18. Bxa7 Ne5 $5 (18... Nxa7
19. Nxf4 Rxf4 20. gxf4 $18) 19. Qd1 Nf3+ 20. Bxf3 Qxf3 21. Nxf4 Rxf4 22. Qxf3
Rxf3 23. Be3 $14) 18... Rxf4 19. Bxf4 Nd4 $1 20. Qa2 $2 (20. Qd1 Bg4 $1 21. Qc1
Bf3 $1 22. Re7 Bxd5 23. cxd5 g5 $19) 20... Nf3+ 21. Kh1 c6 22. Be4 Rxf4 23.
gxf4 Bg4 0-1

