1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 f5 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. d3 Bb4 6. e3 Bxc3+ {Good timing.
Black chops off the Knight and doubles White's c-pawns before White can
reinforce the c3 square with Nge2 or Bd2.} 7. bxc3 d6 8. Ne2 O-O 9. Rb1 Qe8 10.
O-O Kh8 (10... e4 11. d4 Na5 $15 {is similar.}) 11. d4 e4 {Now White's doubled
c-pawns are a logical object of attack.} 12. Ba3 Na5 13. Rb4 b6 14. c5 d5 {
This locks up the center, which proves very useful to Black a few moves down
the road.} (14... dxc5 15. dxc5 Ba6 16. cxb6 axb6 17. Rb1 Rf7 $17) 15. cxb6
axb6 {Black almost always recaptures this way in order to open the a-file.} 16.
Rb1 Rg8 {The Rook is getting out of the line of attack of White's Bishop. But
it is also moving to the file opposite White's King.} 17. Nc1 Nc4 {Positional
domination: Black's Knight owns the queenside.} 18. Bb2 g5 {Very sharp. Black
intends ...f4 with an attack on both sides of the board. This strategy is made
possible by the utterly locked central position; if Black did not have the
center completely locked down, the exposure of his King might be embarrassing.}
19. Bh3 $2 {White develops a plan to exchange off a pair of minor pieces.
Unfortunately for him, it's the wrong pair.} f4 20. Bxc8 Qxc8 {Suddenly White
realizes that the light squares around his King are indefensible.} (20... Qxc8
21. exf4 Qh3 $1 {Now both ...Ng4 and ...gxf4 are deadly threats.} 22. f3 gxf4
23. g4 Ne3 $1 $19 {and a Knight sacrifice on g4 will force mate in a few moves.
}) 0-1

